## Building a Transfer List in Angular

**Mental model:** Two lists (left/right) plus a `Set` of ticked ids spanning both. Move buttons shift ticked items across; the move is filter-out-of-source + concat-into-target, then clear the ticks. Getters drive button enablement. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Two arrays + checked Set
```typescript
left: Item[] = [];
right: Item[] = [];
checked = new Set<number>();
```

### Step 2 — Toggle a tick
```typescript
toggle(id: number): void {
  if (this.checked.has(id)) { this.checked.delete(id); } else { this.checked.add(id); }
}
```

### Step 3 — Move checked across
```typescript
moveRight(): void {
  const moving = this.left.filter((i) => this.checked.has(i.id));
  this.right = [...this.right, ...moving];
  this.left = this.left.filter((i) => !this.checked.has(i.id));
  this.checked = new Set();
}
```

### Step 4 — Enable buttons by side
```typescript
get leftChecked(): boolean { return this.left.some((i) => this.checked.has(i.id)); }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Mixed ticks | Reset `checked` after each move. |
| Empty side | Render an "(empty)" row. |
| Unique ids | Required across both lists. |

**Interview tip:** One shared `checked` Set plus getter-based button enablement keeps it DRY; the move is two array transforms and a reset — say that explicitly rather than maintaining per-list selection state.

